name: Alpha Rogue Hopper
description:
This is a small part that enables the Adventure Force Alpha Rogue to feed darts through a vertical hopper. It is still a Work In Progress, so some parts may change.

You will need to modify the shell, and remove some plastic. You may also need a small amount of Epoxy Putty

It is not particularly reliable, so use at your own risk. I've included the STEP assembly, so modify it at your own risk.

details:
Summary

This is a small part that enables the Adventure Force Alpha Rogue to feed darts through a vertical hopper. It is still a Work In Progress, so some parts may change.

You will need to modify the shell, and remove some plastic. You may also need a small amount of Epoxy Putty

It is not particularly reliable, so use at your own risk. I've included the STEP assembly, so modify it at your own risk.

Print Settings

Printer:

Ender 3

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

Nothing lower than 0.2mm

Infill:

20%

Filament: AMZ3D PLA Lake Blue

Post-Printing

Materials and Tools Needed

-Printed Parts
-Rotary Tool with cutoff wheel
-2x 6-32 3/8" screws, preferably button head
-Sandpaper

Modifying the shell

You will have to remove two parts: The little bridge over the breech and the cover on the left. Then, take the part that has two slots and fasten it to the shell. Next, slip in the part with the two tabs, and put in both screws.

Add in darts, prime it, hope a dart in in the breech, and fire.

name: Balance Scales for low gram weights

creator.name: im_a_bus_yo
creator.first_name: Oh you not getting my first name

description:
I made these scales to measure few- and sub-gram objects using known weights as counterbalance, though can go up 30g. It can tell about 25mg difference at best with good tuning, though it's lacking consistency and needs to be balanced before every measurement. Because of plastic material measurements can be affected by static electricity. For hobby purposes only. For anything scientific buy real scales.

Use thinnest wire possible to create pivot/hang points to reduce friction. First balance the beam, then balance with cups connected adding pieces of tape where needed.

Highest hang point of the mid beam is the least precision but easiest to balance, lowest is the highest precision but hardest to balance

If you want to make your own sub-gram weights:

  1. Get a known weight object, like a coin
  2. Coil up some wire
  3. Cut the coil to same weight as known object and count number of wraps
  4. Cut number of wraps to your desired weight

name: Monoprice Select Mini V1 upgrade for E3D-V6 HotEnd
description:
The stock hotend on the MPSM-iiiP V1 is a nice cheat, but not great for the long haul !

I downloaded, printed and weighed the features of the various designs and wanted several improvements.  This is based on the design by **** justinschmitt **** and it still accepts his fan holder.  I only wanted a ZERO-OFFSET solution.  I really like Justin's overall design the way it slopes back and provides more air space behind the heatsink.  I also like the idea that his mount is modular for those that might want to mount a laser for engraving.

My version of this upgrade provides the following:

 1- nut holders for ease of assembly/disassembly
 2- use of 6-32 or M4-7 hardware
 3- Site Window for Belt Location
 4- Added "tit" on Belt hold down
 5- "just in case" slot to allow for Zip Ties if the Belt slips
 6- Clearance cut for X-Axis sheet metal cover
 7- Weight reduction in Bearing holders
 8- two STL files with exact bearing diameter and printed diameter are provide for sizing
 9- simplified overhang vent
10- strain-relief zip-tie mount for all hot-end wiring

The finished and printed models installed using the original heater, thermistor, and fan with no need to change ANY wiring !!!

The offset following installation was within a half turn (clockwise) of the four bed leveling screws !!!  I credit  justinschmitt for this.

A shout-out also goes to Kadah for his X-End Pullers.  This saved me the trouble of making my own from scratch and more importantly reminded me that the x-End Cap is a bitch to remove and his tool kept me from going animal on my MPSMiiiPv1. **** Kadah also gets a high-five for his AMAZING accurate rendering of the entire Select Mini.  It was nice to be able to check my dimensions against his rendering. ****

This is my first pass at this posting and much more will follow so please look back later....

Enjoy and comment or like as needed......

name: D1 Mini WS2812B LED Case - JST SM connector
description: I wanted a case that had a JST connector with space for cable sleeving. I'm using 1/2 in sleeving and heatshrink. Case is a press fit, it should be very snug. If needed, add a drop of super glue in on corner to hold it in place. I also recommend that you either hot glue or use a zip tie to secure the cable from sliding out.

name: RS_CNC_update
description:
This update permits to replace the 625zz ball bearings of the RS-CNC or the RS-CNC32 by some GT2 pulley 20T 5x10 without teeth.

The fasteners used for assembly are the same as those used for the assembly of the original printed parts.

If you encounter some difficulties to insert the pulleys into the "Y_belt_tensioner_A_pulley" and "Y_belt_tensioner_ B_pulley" parts, file their bearings' supports very slightly. Perform insertion tests to ensure that you do not file the parts too much, otherwise you may to have some lateral loose.
